rComments: Studying is a breeze since you don't need to read the cases to do well. But read the cases. Time management on exams isn't much of an issue since his exams are multiple choice. Go to every class and take good notes and that's basically your outline. He's a really sweet guy too. Very approachable and very kind.
Excellent speaker, engaging lecturer, hilarious storyteller. He is able to make complex subjects quite clear. Handouts for every aspect of the class. All exams are multiple choice.

The exams are like the LSAT, if you understand the material and prepare, you'll be okay. He is an amazing professor and one of the highlights at uOttawa. Would definitely recommend if his exams weren't so difficult. Either way - is a privilege to have him! Extremely clear, funny, engaging, super caring about students well-being. Genuinely good guy.
Seriously awesome. He is not only kind, he clearly loves teaching and takes it seriously. He is NEVER unprepared for class. Plus he's hilarious. I could not recommend this prof more.

Professor Mayeda is by far one of the best professors I have at at the University of Ottawa, Faculty of Law. He explains things extremely well, he is down-to-earth, and he is brilliant. Highly recommended.

Tough grader. Had him for admin law which is a tough subject as it is. Very kind personality and very engaging, such a sweetheart for lack of better word. Very approachable outside of class both in office hours and by email. Great professor and overall recommended!

His first yr crim class is tough. Readings are incredibly dense but he is probably the most dedicated and kind prof at the law school. His tests are notoriously difficult but fair. He is an engaging lecturer who is humble and really cares about his students and their well-being. He really wants you to succeed and will do everything he can to help
teacherRatingTags: ['Get ready to read', 'Gives good feedback', 'EXTRA CREDIT']

rComments: He's a kind, funny, and brilliant professor. He truly cares about his students and he puts a lot of thought into his teaching. 1 of the best. But, there's around 100+ pages of readings per week (his syllabus is 24 pages long), & you'll feel exhausted after every lecture. He takes a very academic approach more suitable for a seminar-type course.
His multiple choice exams are seriously tough. You're pretty much rewriting the LSAT looking for all the places you might get tricked. Otherwise engaging and humorous lecturer.

Very interesting professor and a great lecturer, but he switched his exams to multiple choice-based and those are horrifically painful. Because he has a philosophy background, his multiple choice questions are exceptionally tricky/wishy-washy. He's still one of the best first year crim prof's though and he genuinely cares about his students.

Loved him! Extremely helpful, willing to answer all questions in class (even the useless ones asked by certain students). Midterm is a no fail, so lets you get an idea of what he expects. Did horrible on the midterm, and aced the final...overall A-...HIGHLY RECOMMEND!

One of my favourite first year profs. He is incredibly kind and you can tell he really cares about his students. Exams were fun and I didn't have time issues. He really enjoys philosophy and social justice/feminism issues, but he welcomes and respects all perspectives, which is very important IMO. I will take his classes again!

Best professor of my 1st year of law school. When I look back on this school year 10 years from now he will be the prof that I remember from my 1st year. He really goes out of his way to help his students. If I were not in his class, I would be jealous of the students who are in his class.

Very philisophical and whimsical, enjoyable prof. Super nice and friendly. Focused on social justice. He is more of an academic crim prof, though. If your want to actually practice criminal law, try for Poccacio. His fact patterns on exams are hilarious and twisted.

Overrated prof I think. He trails off way too much in lecture with stories. He addresses very stupid, off topic questions from students and spends lots of class time answering them. He is better for a seminar class than a lecture class. Although helpful and attentive to students, his expectations are sometimes unclear and his exams are confusing.

The peoples champ. Everyone loved Graham. Had him for small group.  A+ guy, very helpful, hip and fun.  Went WAY out of his way to help students with whatever was needed (papers, exam prep, ref letters, you name it).  One of the few proffs that care.  Walking brain, if he ever goes out into practice agian and u end up on the opp side, your screwed!

He's a nice guy, but knows absolutely nothing about criminal law. We didn't learn a thing from that class. Students were practically teaching him - can you imagine first year students teaching a Prof?!!!
